Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, U.S.—No policy pits good economics so directly against good politics as do food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue facing the three most important new leaders in the world: Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
The subsidy cuts that Xixi faces are turning out to be better than expected.
On the contrary, Modi is facing a worse situation than expected, which could even jeopardize the long-awaited WTO agreement.
The situation that Jokowi faces remains unclear.
In July, Saied accomplished a feat rarely achieved by leaders in North Africa and the Middle East: he significantly reduced long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41 to 78 percent.
Strangely enough, there was almost no opposition to the demonstration.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained at extremely low levels, often being used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often led to unrest, and even the overthrow of governments.
But the Sicilian government seems to be making progress in this area as well.
The bread subsidy has been cut by 13%.
Xi Xi had no choice.
Even after the reduction in subsidies, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year still reaches 10% of GDP (which would have been 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, almost no one anticipated that Xi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, would act more swiftly than Modi. Modi secured the prime ministership through an overwhelming democratic majority in India, where there was a strong desire for comprehensive economic reforms.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who began his tenure in October, inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy program worth up to $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), which has placed a heavy burden on the country.
The outgoing Susilo had already taken a courageous first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Zulkifli's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he openly stated his plan to implement the reductions gradually over four years.
Economists are confident in opposing commodity subsidies because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfect competitive fields, the government — not large private monopolies — is the root.
Critics of the "invisible hand" point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
The sharp controversy surrounding subsidies for food and fossil fuels arises because they are often justified under the banners of environmental protection or equality, yet in reality, they do little to advance these goals and often produce the opposite effect.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Gasoline subsidies in most countries benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of the liquefied petroleum gas subsidies reached the poorest population, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the wealthiest individuals.
Globally, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies reach the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies also have the potential to distort public policy, as evidenced by the Modi government's efforts to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
In fact, the Modi government's rejection of the WTO compromise has undone the most significant progress made in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in poor countries; while at other times they benefit producers at the expense of consumers, particularly in wealthy countries.
India's policy aims to have both.
As a result, India accomplished a feat: supplying wheat to consumers at artificially low prices while simultaneously facing oversupply, as farmers could obtain high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs—electricity, water, and fertilizers—while the environment is being destroyed.)
The government purchased large quantities of corrupt rice and wheat, while the small portion distributed to consumers was both corrupt and failed to meet the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and procurement support.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it was impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply rejected the Trade Facilitation Agreement, which the World Trade Organization had eagerly anticipated.
Once subsidies are implemented, they are very difficult to reclaim.
When world commodity prices rise (as they have over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from these shocks.
But people accustomed to government-set prices for food and energy will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument for never implementing subsidies in the first place.
But this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining them is necessarily the wisest choice for a savvy politician.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap eventually leads to a sharper rise in retail prices, slow-moving leaders are unlikely to benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, while cutting subsidies for food and energy, other more efficient measures to support low-income populations should be implemented.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in implementing effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer programs like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries are forced to make adjustments only when a budget crisis occurs, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate the suffering.
Cunning politicians might be wise to implement unpopular adjustments right at the beginning of their tenure.
Both Jokowi and Xi have adopted this policy.
Modi, who had won a resounding victory in the elections under the slogan of market reforms, has now fallen behind.
